{"id":"project-LICHEN-id1p","title":"unprotect_request may accept 0xFF in class E options as payload marker","description":"File: rust/lichen-oscore/src/lib.rs
Lines: 434-439

When parsing decrypted plaintext in unprotect_request:
```rust
let rest = &plaintext[1..];
// Find payload marker
let marker_pos = rest.iter().position(|&b| b == 0xFF);

let (options_slice, payload_slice) = match marker_pos {
    Some(pos) => (&rest[..pos], &rest[pos + 1..]),
    None => (rest, &[][..]),
};
```

This finds the FIRST occurrence of 0xFF in the decrypted content. However, CoAP Class E options are binary-encoded and could theoretically contain 0xFF in option VALUES (not option headers).

Per RFC 7252 Section 3, the payload marker 0xFF is specifically an illegal option delta (15) with illegal length (15). In the option delta-length encoding, 0xFF can only appear as the end-of-options marker.

However, the OSCORE plaintext contains Class E options in their wire format. If an option VALUE contains 0xFF, the parsing would incorrectly treat it as the payload marker.

Example: An If-Match option (0x0D) with value 0xFF would be encoded as [0x01, 0xFF] (delta=1, len=1, value=0xFF). The 0xFF would be incorrectly treated as payload marker.

Impact: Incorrect parsing of messages with 0xFF in option values.

Fix: Parse options using CoAP delta-length decoding, not simple byte search.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:38:26.189682Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:38:26.189715Z"}
